## Executive Summary

- **Litigation as structured engineering:** The Mayron paradigm treats legal disputes as element-based problems requiring systematic record-building rather than relying on legal expertise or emotional narratives.
- **Core methodology:** Uses Element Mappers (requirement checklists), Evidence Ledgers (contemporaneous documentation), and Motion Scaffolding (court-ready templates) to build verifiable records from day one.
- **AI-powered workflow:** Three-tier AI system (Architect, Builder, Inspector) creates a self-sufficient litigation process with built-in quality control, functioning as a "one-person law firm."
- **Access to justice focus:** Designed to empower self-represented litigants by transforming litigation from arcane art to information organization, lowering economic barriers to competent advocacy.
- **Demonstrated effectiveness:** Early success in straightforward cases (landlord-tenant, consumer protection) where systematic documentation forces substantive engagement over procedural dismissal.
- **Significant limitations:** Less effective for complex cases requiring expert testimony or nuanced theory; success varies widely by jurisdiction and judicial attitudes toward pro se filigants.
- **Unresolved ethical questions:** Raises regulatory concerns about unauthorized practice of law, liability for AI-generated errors, and whether sophisticated legal automation crosses the line from education to service.
- **Systemic implications:** Influencing legal education and small firm practice while challenging traditional professional gatekeeping; may fundamentally reshape how justice system balances access versus quality control.

